export const GROUP_DESCRIPTIONS: Record<string, string> = {
  Analysts: `Analysts are defined by their love of ideas, rational analysis, and the pursuit of mastery. They are drawn to systems, theories, and the kind of deep understanding that allows them to see what others miss. Ambitious and intellectually independent, Analysts often set high standards for themselves and struggle with environments that prioritise conformity over competence. They can appear blunt or remote, not from indifference, but because they naturally separate people from ideas. Their greatest gift is their capacity to think clearly through complexity. Their growth edge is developing the patience and relational warmth to bring others along on the journey their minds have already completed.`,

  Diplomats: `Diplomats are driven by meaning, authenticity, and a deep care for people. They see potential where others see only what is, and they are energised by the possibility of positive change \u2014 in themselves, in others, and in the world. Idealistic and perceptive, Diplomats have a rare ability to understand the inner lives of the people around them and to communicate in ways that genuinely move and inspire. They can struggle with perfectionism, with the gap between how things are and how they feel they should be, and with the emotional cost of absorbing the pain of others. Their greatest gift is their capacity for genuine human connection. Their growth edge is learning when to release the perfect in favour of the possible.`,

  Sentinels: `Sentinels are the world\u2019s dependable builders \u2014 practical, responsible, and deeply committed to the structures, institutions, and relationships that provide stability and order. They trust experience over theory and value tradition not for its own sake but because it has been tested. Sentinels take their obligations seriously, often carrying more than their fair share of the load with quiet reliability. They can struggle with change that disrupts established systems and may find it difficult to adapt when their expectations of how things should be done are challenged. Their greatest gift is their reliability and the security they create for those around them. Their growth edge is developing flexibility and the confidence to let go of what no longer serves.`,

  Explorers: `Explorers are the most present and adaptable of all the groups \u2014 practical, spontaneous, and energised by immediate experience. They are masters of their physical environment, excellent in crisis, and gifted at finding the most direct and practical path through any situation. They resist constraint and thrive when they have the freedom to respond to what is actually happening rather than what was planned. Explorers can struggle with long-term planning, with routines that seem to exist for their own sake, and with contexts that demand sustained focus on the abstract. Their greatest gift is their ability to act quickly and effectively in the real world. Their growth edge is developing the capacity to honour commitments to a future they have not yet experienced.`,
};

export const MODIFIER_ASSERTIVE = `There is a quality of settled confidence in the way you move through the world. You do not depend on external validation to feel secure in your judgements \u2014 you have developed a relatively stable relationship with your own capabilities, and when you make a decision you tend to trust it rather than spending significant energy second-guessing after the fact. Stress is something you manage effectively; it does not tend to linger, distort your thinking, or hold you back from acting when action is needed. You are less likely than many people to take setbacks personally, and your ability to separate your sense of self-worth from the inevitable difficulties of any significant endeavour is a genuine strength. This equanimity is most valuable in high-pressure situations \u2014 your steadiness tends to steady others around you as well. The potential growth edge for Assertive types is a certain blindness to the value of self-examination. The confidence that keeps you moving forward can occasionally prevent you from slowing down enough to notice what has been missed, what someone else sees that you do not, or what internal development might actually serve you. Remaining genuinely curious \u2014 not as an intellectual position but as a lived practice \u2014 is what allows the Assertive type\u2019s natural confidence to keep deepening rather than calcifying.`;

export const MODIFIER_TURBULENT = `There is a powerful inner compass that drives you \u2014 a restless awareness of the gap between where you are and where you could be, between how something went and how it should have gone, between who you are today and who you are capable of becoming. This sensitivity is not a flaw; it is the engine of your growth. Turbulent types often achieve at a very high level precisely because they cannot settle for good enough when they can see that better is possible. Your attunement to feedback \u2014 from the environment, from others, from your own inner critic \u2014 makes you genuinely responsive to what needs to change. You are more likely than most to learn from mistakes, to take feedback seriously rather than defensively, and to invest in your own development with genuine seriousness. The challenge that this sensitivity brings is the emotional cost of carrying it. The same awareness that makes you a high achiever can generate patterns of self-doubt, excessive rumination about the past, and a tendency to experience stress more intensely than circumstances require. The most important work for Turbulent types is not the suppression of this sensitivity \u2014 it is its redirection. The energy that goes into worry and self-criticism, when redirected toward purposeful effort and self-compassion, is transformative. Your sensitivity is a gift. The question is whether it is working for you or against you.`;

export const MODIFIER_COOPERATIVE = `You are someone who genuinely values the quality of the collective over the achievement of the individual. Group harmony, shared success, and the experience of working alongside others toward something meaningful are not just pleasant additions to the work \u2014 they are part of what makes the work worthwhile. You tend to be aware of social dynamics, sensitive to how decisions land with the people around you, and naturally inclined to seek consensus or at least genuine buy-in before moving forward. This orientation makes you an effective collaborator and a natural bridge-builder in environments where alignment across different people and perspectives is necessary. You are probably the person who notices when someone has been left out, who takes the time to bring a dissenting voice into the conversation, and who finds satisfaction not just in the outcome but in the quality of the journey that got there. The potential growth edge for Cooperative types is the management of this orientation when it conflicts with clear individual conviction. There are moments when the most genuinely helpful thing \u2014 to a team, a project, a relationship \u2014 is to hold a position firmly even when it creates friction, to name something that others are avoiding, or to act on a strong personal judgement rather than waiting for consensus. Learning when to prioritise the group\u2019s comfort and when to prioritise the group\u2019s progress is the ongoing discernment that Cooperative types are called to develop.`;

export const MODIFIER_SELFDIRECTED = `You are someone who navigates primarily from an internal reference point. Your standards, your goals, your assessment of your own performance \u2014 these are set by you, not by the expectations of the group around you. This independence of orientation is a genuine strength: you are not easily swayed from positions you have thought through, you can work effectively without the ongoing encouragement of others, and you are less susceptible than most to social pressure that pulls toward conformity rather than quality. There is a clarity and a groundedness to your engagement that comes from knowing what you are trying to do and why, independently of what the crowd thinks about it. You probably do some of your most effective work alone, or in small groups of people you have specifically chosen because of the quality of what they bring rather than the social cohesion they provide. The potential growth edge for Self-directed types is the consistent and conscious investment in the relational fabric that makes individual work possible and sustainable over time. Independent orientation does not mean independence from others \u2014 it means that your compass is yours. The people around you, the quality of the relationships you build, the degree to which you invite genuine feedback and allow it to reach you \u2014 these matter for the long game. The most effective Self-directed types are those who pair their independence of judgement with a genuine curiosity about what others see that they do not.`;
